      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. that sounds pretty scary lol. u mentioned it's way too aggressive... is there like any specific wording in there that's especially sneaky? like are there certain words that act as red flags that i should look out for in other contracts so i don't get caught off guard?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, there are several specific \"red flag\" phrases in that clause that act like a trap for freelancers. The most sneaky part is the phrase **\"any and all losses, damages, liabilities,\"** combined with the word **\"including reasonable attorneys' fees.\"**\n\nThis wording is designed to be so broad (\"any and all\") that it creates a \"net\" where even tiny mistakes or third-party claims get caught, forcing you to pay for their legal team's bill hours just to defend yourself. In the legal world, this is often called a \"catch-all\" indemnity, and it is a classic tactic used by companies to shift all risk onto the individual worker.\n\nTo protect yourself in future contracts, look out for these specific terms that signal an unfair trap:\n*   **\"Indemnify, defend, and hold harmless\"**: This is the standard \"aggressive\" trio. If you see this without specific limits, it means you are taking on *all* their risks, not just your own.\n*   **\"Any and all\"**: This is the \"catch-all\" phrase. It removes any boundaries on what you are responsible for, covering even things that might be the other party's own fault.",
